<HEADLINE>
<P>
TENNIS ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
SAMPRAS IS A WINNER IN SWEDEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pete Sampras, playing in his first ATP Tour event since becoming the youngest 
U.S. Open champion in history Sept. 9, defeated David Wheaton, 7-6 (7-3), 5-7, 
6-4, Friday to reach the semifinals of the $1.1-million Stockholm Open. 
</P>
<P>
Sampras has been sidelined by shin splints. 
</P>
<P>
Other quarterfinal winners included Stefan Edberg and Boris Becker. 
</P>
<P>
Edberg, the world's top-ranked player, outlasted No. 7-seeded Brad Gilbert, 
6-4, 3-6, 6-1, before 12,350 at the Globe Arena. 
</P>
<P>
Becker, who has lost only one indoor match this fall, to third-ranked Ivan 
Lendl in Japan early last month, beat No. 9-seeded Goran Ivanisevic of 
Yugoslavia, 6-4, 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
Sampras will play Alexander Volkov of the Soviet Union in the semifinals. 
Volkov beat 1989 world junior champion Nicklas Kulti of Sweden, 6-2, 6-1, in a 
match between unseeded players. 
</P>
<P>
Second-seeded Jennifer Capriati defeated qualifier Maria Strand- lund of 
Sweden, 6-1, 6-4, to advance to the semifinals of the $150,000 Puerto Rico Open 
at San Juan. 
</P>
<P>
No. 6 Gigi Fernandez defeated Audra Keller, 6-1, 4-6, 6-4, to set up a 
Capriati-Fernandez semifinal today. 
</P>
<P>
Top-seeded Zina Garrison outlasted No. 8 Ann Grossman, 7-6 (7-4), 3-6, 6-1, and 
unseeded Carrie Cunningham also advanced when she defeated upstart Argentine 
Florencia Labat, 6-3, 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
Capriati defeated Meredith McGrath, 6-3, 6-2, in a match postponed Thursday 
because of rain. 
</P>
<P>
Steffi Graf defeated Nathalie Tauziat, 6-2, 6-4, to advance to the semifinals 
of a WITA indoor tournament at Brighton, England. 
</P>
<P>
In today's semifinals, Graf meets Catarina Lindqvist of Sweden, who beat 
Italy's Cathy Caverzasio, 6-2, 6-3. Third-seeded Helena Sukova also moved into 
the semifinals with a 6-1, 6-1 victory over Sara Gomer of Britain. 
</P>
<P>
Top-seeded Debbie Graham saved three match points against UCLA's Kimberly Po 
and went on to join two Stanford teammates in the semifinals of the 
All-American Championships at the Riviera Tennis Club. 
</P>
<P>
Graham, the 1990 NCAA singles champion, beat Po, 6-3, 3-6, 7-5, in the second 
round. Po led 5-4 in the third set and was ahead 40-15 in the 10th game before 
Graham rallied. 
</P>
<P>
Graham, who had match point against Monica Seles before losing in the 
semifinals of an exhibition tournament last summer, then beat Caryn Moss of 
Georgia, 6-4, 6-3, in the quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
Graham will face Emilie Viqueira of California in today's semifinals. The other 
match will pit defending champion and second-seeded Sandra Birch against 
Heather Williams. 
</P>
<P>
Birch, the 1989 NCAA champion, eased to victories over Iwalani McCalla of UCLA, 
6-2, 6-3, and Lisa Albano of California, 6-2, 6-1. 
</P>
<P>
Willens upset fourth-seeded Shannan McCarthy of Georgia, 4-6, 7-6 (8-6), 6-3, 
in the second round and then beat qualifier Sakolwan Kacharoen of San Diego, 
4-6, 7-6 (7-3), 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
Viqueira defeated No. 3-seeded Trisha Laux of USC, 5-7, 7-5, 7-6 (7-5), in a 
four-hour marathon in the second round and then beat Kansas' Eveline Hamers, 
6-0, 6-1, in the quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
Richard Fromberg, a clay-court specialist, and John Fitzgerald were named to a 
preliminary Australian team for the Davis Cup final against the United States 
Nov. 30-Dec. 2 at St. Petersburg, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
They join Pat Cash, a former Wimbledon champion, Wally Masur, Darren Cahill and 
Mark Kratzmann, who were members of the Australia team that defeated Argentina, 
5-0, in the semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
Fromberg is the highest-ranked Australian singles player at 28th on the ATP 
Tour computer, and has won two clay-court tournaments this year. 
</P>
<P>
Fitzgerald gets another chance after missing the semifinal against Argentina. 
He played in the first two rounds, against France and New Zealand, both on 
grass courts. 
</P>
<P>
Jason Stoltenberg, Todd Woodbridge and Mark Woodforde were dropped from the 
eight-man squad which prepared for Argentina. 
</P>
<P>
Cash and Masur will probably play singles against Andre Agassi and Michael 
Chang on the clay surface being prepared for the final. 
</P>
<P>
Rick Leach and Jim Pugh will team in doubles for the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
