<HEADLINE>
<P>
BATTLESHIP IOWA BEING PUT IN MOTHBALLS AGAIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NORFOLK, Va. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Navy decommissioned the battleship Iowa on Friday, retiring the World War 
II-era ship that became a casualty of Pentagon budget cuts after an April, 
1989, gun turret explosion that killed 47 crewmen. 
</P>
<P>
The Iowa, decommissioned for the third time, is being mothballed six years 
after a $348.7-million renovation returned it to active duty. 
</P>
<P>
Also being retired is the battleship New Jersey, based in Long Beach, Calif. It 
is slated to be taken out of service in February. Retirement of the vessels 
will leave the United States with two active Iowa-class battleships, the 
Wisconsin and the Missouri. 
</P>
