<HEADLINE>
<P>
MEETING OF EVANGELICAL THEOLOGIANS TO DISCUSS SHIFT IN CONCEPT OF DEITY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An array of noted evangelical theologians will begin a three-day conference 
Thursday at Christ College Irvine to discuss a what is termed a major trend in 
conservative Christian thinking away from an angry, justice-meting God to a 
loving, forgiving deity. 
</P>
<P>
"All evangelicals would want to say . . . that God is both friend and judge," 
said the Rev. Michael Horton of Anaheim, president of the conference-sponsoring 
Christians United for Reformation. 
</P>
<P>
But the emphasis has been shifting toward preaching and teaching about God's 
love, said Horton. 
</P>
<P>
Speaking for the new perspective will be Clark Pinnock of McMaster Divinity 
College, Ontario, Canada, Robert Webber of Wheaton College and Richard Rice of 
Loma Linda University. 
</P>
<P>
Talking about the older theology are Robert Strimple and W. Robert Godfrey of 
Westminster Theological Seminary in Escondido, Rod Rosenbladt of Christ College 
and Horton. 
</P>
<P>
The meeting will begin 9 a.m. Thursday. Registration is $50. 
</P>
</TEXT>
